{"repo": "pdfarranger/pdfarranger", "pull_number": 1320, "instance_id": "pdfarranger__pdfarranger-1320", "issue_numbers": [1317], "base_commit": "d68e9896132dfd591cc11325010fd976c59d8dff", "patch": "diff --git a/.github/workflows/manual.yml b/.github/workflows/manual.yml\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 000000000..6bf06f050\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/.github/workflows/manual.yml\n@@ -0,0 +1,51 @@\n+name: Manual\n+on:\n+  workflow_dispatch:\n+    inputs:\n+      pikepdf_tag:\n+        description: 'Git tag for pikepdf (e.g., v10.2.0)'\n+        required: true\n+        type: string\n+        default: 'main'\n+      qpdf_tag:\n+        description: 'Git tag for qpdf (e.g., v12.3.1)'\n+        required: true\n+        type: string\n+        default: 'main'\n+jobs:\n+  pdfarranger-ci-tests-using-pikepdf-and-qpdf-built-from-source:\n+    runs-on: ubuntu-latest\n+    container:\n+      image: ghcr.io/pdfarranger/pdfarranger-pikepdf-qpdf-dev-docker-ci:1.0.0\n+    steps:\n+      - name: Checkout pdfarranger Git repository\n+        uses: actions/checkout@v6\n+      - name: Build libqpdf\n+        run: |\n+          git clone https://github.com/qpdf/qpdf.git\n+          cd qpdf\n+          git checkout ${{ inputs.qpdf_tag }}\n+          echo QPDF_SOURCE_TREE=$PWD >> $GITHUB_ENV\n+          cmake -S . -B build -DCMAKE_BUILD_TYPE=RelWithDebInfo -DBUILD_SHARED_LIBS=ON\n+          cmake --build build --parallel --target libqpdf\n+          echo QPDF_BUILD_LIBDIR=$PWD/build/libqpdf >> $GITHUB_ENV\n+      - name: Set up venv\n+        run: |\n+          python3 -m venv --system-site-packages virtenv\n+          echo \"$GITHUB_WORKSPACE/virtenv/bin\" >> $GITHUB_PATH\n+          echo \"VIRTUAL_ENV=$GITHUB_WORKSPACE/virtenv\" >> $GITHUB_ENV\n+      - name: Upgrade pip\n+        run: pip install --upgrade pip\n+      - name: Build pikepdf\n+        run: |\n+          git clone https://github.com/pikepdf/pikepdf.git\n+          cd pikepdf\n+          git checkout ${{ inputs.pikepdf_tag }}\n+          env QPDF_SOURCE_TREE=$QPDF_SOURCE_TREE QPDF_BUILD_LIBDIR=$QPDF_BUILD_LIBDIR \\\n+          pip install -e .\n+      - name: Install pdfaranger\n+        run: pip install -v .[image]\n+      - name: Dogtail Tests\n+        run: python3 -X tracemalloc -u -m unittest -v -f tests.test\n+      - name: Exporter Tests\n+        run: python3 -X tracemalloc -u -m unittest -v -f tests.test_exporter\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "PDF Arranger as test suite for qpdf\n> I was just wondering, if there was a convenient way for you to run your test suite against qpdf main,  would it make  sense to give you a few days notice of any planned releases? \n\n _Originally posted by @m-holger in [#1312](https://github.com/pdfarranger/pdfarranger/issues/1312#issuecomment-3764189794)_\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "> Yeah even though I can remember only on other instance where pikepdf/qpdf broke a feature it still sounds like a good idea to use it for testing before release. (I'm surprised the distros are updating qpdf that fast tbh.)\n> I believe that should be quite simple to set up too with Github actions - we already run the test suit we'd just need to pull and build qpdf (maybe also pikepdf) and run it with those versions. (Or reuse nightly builds in case you have those somewhere.)\n> \n> But for priorities I'd rather fix this issue at hand first, do you already have a lead or are more eyes on the matter needed? \n\n _Originally posted by @dreua in [#1312](https://github.com/pdfarranger/pdfarranger/issues/1312#issuecomment-3765646693)_\nI do have a WIP on this. It is possible to use a \"workflow_dispatch\", which allows the test to be run on demand from a menu on actions page.\n\n\n\nThat is great news! I'm thinking maybe we can do the same thing with pikepdf. (Or at least offer it to the pikepdf devs.)\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/pdfarranger/pdfarranger/commit/12cb7ca22ac64fffd1986bc58530c87820d50448"], "created_at": "2026-01-23T15:55:09Z"}
{"repo": "pdfarranger/pdfarranger", "pull_number": 1365, "instance_id": "pdfarranger__pdfarranger-1365", "issue_numbers": [1363], "base_commit": "050e21b0396d1a5c44b9307d772c37ee0d4c402d", "patch": "diff --git a/pdfarranger/pdfarranger.py b/pdfarranger/pdfarranger.py\nindex 50c3c71d3..11c694d9f 100644\n--- a/pdfarranger/pdfarranger.py\n+++ b/pdfarranger/pdfarranger.py\n@@ -2214,6 +2214,15 @@ def iv_dnd_get_data(self, _iconview, _context,\n             return\n         selection_data.set(selection_data.get_target(), 8, data.encode())\n \n+    @staticmethod\n+    def _is_noop_move(data, ref_to, before):\n+        \"\"\"Check if a move would not change page order.\"\"\"\n+        indices = sorted(int(p) for p in data)\n+        target_idx = ref_to.get_path().get_indices()[0]\n+        insert_pos = target_idx if before else target_idx + 1\n+        continuous = len(indices) == indices[-1] - indices[0] + 1\n+        return continuous and indices[0] <= insert_pos <= indices[-1] + 1\n+\n     def iv_dnd_received_data(self, iconview, context, _x, _y,\n                              selection_data, _target_id, etime):\n         \"\"\"Handles received data by drag and drop in iconview\"\"\"\n@@ -2234,6 +2243,8 @@ def iv_dnd_received_data(self, iconview, context, _x, _y,\n         target = selection_data.get_target().name()\n         if target == 'MODEL_ROW_INTERN':\n             move = context.get_selected_action() & Gdk.DragAction.MOVE\n+            if move and ref_to and self._is_noop_move(data, ref_to, before):\n+                return\n             self.undomanager.commit(\"Move\" if move else \"Copy\")\n             self.set_unsaved(True)\n             data.sort(key=int, reverse=not before)\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "False \"unsaved\" state on accidental micro-drag - accessibility concern for motor-impaired users\nFirst of all, thanks for maintaining pdfarranger :-)\n\nI ran into a usability issue that I think is worth fixing, especially for users with reduced motor precision.\n\n**What happens:**\n\nWhen a user clicks on a page thumbnail and moves the mouse by just a few pixels before releasing (accidental micro-drag), pdfarranger marks the document as modified and shows a \"Save changes?\" dialog on close, even though no page was actually reordered.\n\nThis is particularly confusing for elderly users or people with tremor, for whom a slight unintentional mouse movement during a click is common. The unexpected save dialog creates confusion (\"Did I accidentally change something?\") and can lead to data loss if the user clicks \"Discard\" out of panic.\n\n**Root cause (`pdfarranger.py`, line 1808):**\n\n`set_unsaved(True)` is called unconditionally when any internal DnD gesture completes, before checking whether the page order actually changed:\n\n```python\nself.set_unsaved(True)   # fires before any position check\n```\n\nThis also conflicts with GNOME HIG (\"only present a save dialog if the document has actually been modified\") and ISO 9241-110 Principle 4 (error tolerance).\n\n**Proposed fix:** Compare page order before and after the operation:\n\n```python\nold_order = [model.get_value(model.get_iter(Gtk.TreePath(i)), 0).filename\n             for i in range(model.iter_n_children(None))]\n# ... existing insert/remove operations ...\nnew_order = [model.get_value(model.get_iter(Gtk.TreePath(i)), 0).filename\n             for i in range(model.iter_n_children(None))]\nif old_order != new_order:\n    self.undomanager.commit(\"Move\" if move else \"Copy\")\n    self.set_unsaved(True)\n```\n\n**Steps to reproduce:**\n1. Open any multi-page PDF\n2. Click a page thumbnail, move mouse 3-5 px, release without intentional reorder\n3. Close pdfarranger -> save dialog appears despite no change\n", "hints_text": "Thank you for bringing this issue to our attention and for the well written bug report \ud83d\udc4d\n\nWhile testing I also noticed that \"undo\" does not correctly clear the \"unsaved\" state, it just stays unsaved forever.\nI think the proposed fix is fine. Do you want to make a PR?\n\n", "all_hints_text": "Thank you for bringing this issue to our attention and for the well written bug report \ud83d\udc4d\n\nWhile testing I also noticed that \"undo\" does not correctly clear the \"unsaved\" state, it just stays unsaved forever.\nI think the proposed fix is fine. Do you want to make a PR?\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/pdfarranger/pdfarranger/commit/ce0951d85762193d1ba7f2754513e77280e41e00", "https://github.com/pdfarranger/pdfarranger/commit/48ff60fae02e27213f0476c6188f8d2d4aaff893"], "created_at": "2026-04-10T17:32:38Z"}
{"repo": "pdfarranger/pdfarranger", "pull_number": 1379, "instance_id": "pdfarranger__pdfarranger-1379", "issue_numbers": [1376], "base_commit": "c436fed9baaebe5f1fb8f36b236a7dc34a244c60", "patch": "diff --git a/.prospector.yaml b/.prospector.yaml\nnew file mode 100644\nindex 000000000..f89794e43\n--- /dev/null\n+++ b/.prospector.yaml\n@@ -0,0 +1,4 @@\n+pydocstyle:\n+  disable:\n+    - D203  # blank line before class docstring conflicting with D211\n+    - D212  # multi-line docstring summary style conflict with D213\n", "test_patch": "", "problem_statement": "Contradictory Codacy warnings\nI get Codacy CI warnings about docstrings no matter how I format them in a PR, because two pairs of rules are mutually contradictory:\n\n- D203 requires 1 blank line before a class docstring, while D211 forbids any blank lines before a class docstring \n- D212 requires the summary line to start on the first line of a multi-line docstring, while D213 requires it to start on the second line\n\nI think these warnings are coming from pydocstyle, which is designed so you pick a convention (e.g. convention = pep257) which selects one from each pair and ignores the other.\n\nPlease could you fix this, either by adding a pydocstyle convention to setup.cfg/pyproject.toml (if Codacy respects that), or by configuring it in the Codacy dashboard directly?\n", "hints_text": "\n\n", "all_hints_text": "I'm not yet sure if this worked:\n```\npydocstyle:\n  disable:\n    - D203  # blank line before class docstring conflicting with D211\n    - D212  # multi-line docstring summary style conflict with D213\n```\n\n\n\n", "commit_urls": ["https://github.com/pdfarranger/pdfarranger/commit/f39f9f47be63feab651ecdfe49e0a80620868d89"], "created_at": "2026-04-25T04:27:54Z"}
